{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "While GNNs have enabled the modeling of relationships between users, a limitation emerges as each edge connects only limited dimensions, leading to a loss of representation of complex relationships between nodes.",
    "As an extension of GNNs, HGNNs (Hypergraph Neural Networks) have emerged as a method that enhances the representation of graphstructured data with higher-level relations [26,31].",
    "Studies have demonstrated the utility of HGNNs in modeling non-pairwise relationships and improving the classification of such data structures within social networks [32].",
    "Recently, researchers have developed a hierarchical two-layer, self-supervised hyperedge neural network to classify users' social networks and a novel graph algorithm to learn and analyze the patterns of users' interactions within social environments [30].",
    "These advancements highlight the potential of hypergraphs in enhancing the granularity of sociological analysis, offering new perspectives on user interaction patterns and environmental influence."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
